<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-991-352  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 991 352.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Dec 18 1989 v10 n50 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Speech recognition: where it is, where it's going: say-anythingcapability still on the drawing board.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilkinson, Stephanie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Developers of voice-activated computers and speech recognitionsystems have made great strides, and their current researchfocuses on vocabulary size, speaker independence, and continuousversus discrete commands.andP;  IBM has demonstrated Tangora, a20,000-word speaker-dependent voice recognition system, and iscurrently conducting research on continuous-speech systems.andO;Digitech Inc is attempting to emulate the human hearing system inorder to develop speaker-independent systems, and plans to marketa $50 voice dialer for telephones by Feb 1990.andP;  Kurzweil AppliedIntelligence Inc expects to have a continuous-speech system on amicrocomputer by 1993.andP;  Articulate Systems Inc markets the VoiceNavigator, a device that can be programmed to recognize spokencommands that are then executed by a Macintosh computer.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (research)Digitech Inc. (research)Kurzweil Applied Intelligence Inc. (research)Articulate Systems Inc. (products).andO;Topic:     Voice SynthesisVoice RecognitionResearch and Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>